# 🛡 AntiWorm

> A standalone, cross-platform worm detection and quarantine tool — built as a focused alternative to bundled AV suites.

![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.10+-blue) ![Platform](https://img.shields.io/badge/Platform-Windows%20%7C%20Linux%20%7C%20macOS-green) ![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow)

---

## Why AntiWorm?

Most worm detection is buried inside general-purpose antivirus software. AntiWorm is purpose-built to detect, alert on, and quarantine computer worm behavior specifically — using a layered approach of signature matching, behavioral heuristics, and live network monitoring.

---

## Features

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| 🔍 Signature Detection | Matches files against known worm byte patterns and SHA-256 hashes |
| 🧠 Heuristic Analysis | Scores files on 30+ behavioral indicators (self-replication, persistence, obfuscation) |
| 📡 Network Monitor | Watches live connections for worm-associated ports and rapid connection rates |
| 🔒 Quarantine Vault | Safely isolates threats with full restore capability |
| 📄 Report Generator | Exports findings as HTML, JSON, or TXT |

---

## Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/antiworm.git
cd antiworm
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

---

## Usage

### Scan a directory
```bash
python main.py scan --path /home/user/downloads
python main.py scan --path /home/user/downloads --deep --auto-quarantine
```

### Scan the full system
```bash
sudo python main.py scan --full-system --auto-quarantine
```

### Real-time network monitor
```bash
python main.py monitor --start
```

### Manage quarantine
```bash
python main.py quarantine --list
python main.py quarantine --restore a1b2c3d4
python main.py quarantine --delete a1b2c3d4
python main.py quarantine --purge
```

### Generate a report
```bash
python main.py report --output my_report.html --format html
python main.py report --output findings.json --format json
```

---

## Detection Methods

### 1. Signature-Based Detection
- Compares file SHA-256 hashes against a known worm hash database
- Scans file byte content for known worm patterns (autorun droppers, network share copy commands, SMTP mass-mailers, IRC C2 channels, etc.)
- Flags dangerous double-extension masquerades (`.jpg.exe`, `.pdf.vbs`)

### 2. Heuristic Behavioral Analysis
Scores each file across 30+ rules covering:
- **Self-replication**: `shutil.copy`, `os.system copy`, self-referencing `__file__`
- **Network spreading**: raw socket use, SFTP libraries, IP range scanning
- **Persistence**: Windows registry Run keys, cron jobs, shell startup files
- **Obfuscation**: base64 decode + eval, high-entropy payloads, char-by-char string construction
- **Combo rules**: flags files matching multiple suspicious patterns together

### 3. Network Monitoring (requires psutil)
- Detects connections to known worm-associated ports (SMB 445, IRC 6667, RDP 3389, Telnet 23, etc.)
- Alerts on anomalous connection rates (potential active spreading)

